name: El fantasma de Canterville
comments: When Charly García composes "The Ghost of Canterville", he calls him at León Gieco on the phone and tells him that he has a new song but that it is for the sing it and include it on the debut album at PorSuiGieco . When PorSuiGieco was published in 1976, the last Argentine military dictatorship was already underway. It was inconceivable that a song like "El fantasma de Canterville", which contained phrases like "I was always a fool who believed in legality" or "I have died many times riddled in the city" that stood out notoriously and was sung louder in the Recitals will go unnoticed for military censorship. The group must replace it, in this way Charly writes "Before tour", a song that talks about the life of the musicians during the tours. But León Gieco is not resigned to abandon such a song and decides to include it for its next long duration that will precisely be entitled "El fantasma de Canterville"

name: When It's Moonlight in Mayo
comments: "When It's Moonlight in Mayo (Two Irish Eyes Are Smiling)" was written by Jack Mahoney and Percy Wenrich and published by Leo Feist in 1914.  It is often credited to Irishmen Seamus Kavanagh and Patrick J. Ryan, but the lyrics of their song closely follow those of Mahoney and Wenrich's original.  The song is typically titled "Moonlight in Mayo" and has been popularized by many Irish recording artists (and thus often mistakenly presumed to be of Irish origins).  It was first performed at the Majestic Theater in Chicago in 1914 by Wenrich and his singing partner, Dolly Connolly.  The first recordings were made in 1915.

comments: Traditional Irish-American comic ballad, first published in New York in 1864.  In the ballad, the hod-carrier Tim Finnegan, born "with a love for the liquor", falls from a ladder, breaks his skull, and is thought to be dead. The mourners at his wake become rowdy, and spill whiskey over Finnegan's corpse, causing him to come back to life and join in the celebrations. Whiskey causes both Finnegan's fall and his resurrection. The song is famous for providing the basis of James Joyce's final work, Finnegans Wake (1939).

name: The Great Judgement Morning
comments: The lyrics to the song known as "The Great Judgement Morning" (or I Dreamed that the Great Judgment Morning) came directly from an 1892 poem by Bertram H. Shadduck.  Charlie (Charles) D. Tillman set the text to music and published it as "The Judgment" in 1893 (or possibly 1894).  The musical component has a complicated past as it's been subsequently published with authorship claims by many, including L.L. Pickett in 1894, F.L. Eiland in 1898, R.E. Winsett in 1934, Virgil O. Stamps in 1939, and Renus E. Rich in 1957. L.L. Pickett is solely credited on Homer E. Rodeheaver's 1913 original gospel song as well as the 1930 gospel version by the McCravy Brothers. R.E. Winsett is solely credited on Roy Acuff's 1941 recording.  Acuff's was the first country rendition and it became a hit and now most releases credit Winsett.  However, since there isn't a great distinction musically or lyrically between the performances, SHS is crediting the original copyright holder for the musical aspect, Charlie D. Tillman (and not Pickett or Winsett,...), and crediting the lyrics to Bertram H. Shadduck.
